textDisplay:
The caged patios and bright primary colors of the buildings take me back to when I visited the DR when I was 6 back in 2001.

My Father is Charismatic, so he would talk endlessly on the streets with his friends while he held my hand in front of the Bodega. Bachata would blast out from the Bodega while he just talked and laughed with people he just met.
The sun would set and he would walk me home in the dark with the lights of different bodegas revealing our path.

I remember my Mother telling us to be careful in the streets.
Taxis were motorcycles.
Rats ran across our roof all night.
The power would go out from a little rain.
Our Cousin was choked to death by a man on a motorcycle who tried to steal her necklace off her neck.

My parents still visit Dominican Republic every year for vacation.
My Father loves it because he grew up there.
This video really put into perspective how he really grew up poor.
I’m remembering his stories about him running around barefoot, dealing with consistent power outages, and rats.

My Father loved Trujillo because he hates Haitian immigration. He also signed his mom a deed to a house to live in and raise her kids.
I’m sad to hear theres more Haitian immigrants there…

Hearing them all speak in Spanish with a Dominican dialect, tone, and attitude takes me back to my Childhood.
Thats all I heard all day growing up in a Dominican family.
textOriginal:
The caged patios and bright primary colors of the buildings take me back to when I visited the DR when I was 6 back in 2001. 

My Father is Charismatic, so he would talk endlessly on the streets with his friends while he held my hand in front of the Bodega. Bachata would blast out from the Bodega while he just talked and laughed with people he just met. 
The sun would set and he would walk me home in the dark with the lights of different bodegas revealing our path. 

I remember my Mother telling us to be careful in the streets. 
Taxis were motorcycles. 
Rats ran across our roof all night. 
The power would go out from a little rain. 
Our Cousin was choked to death by a man on a motorcycle who tried to steal her necklace off her neck. 

My parents still visit Dominican Republic every year for vacation.
My Father loves it because he grew up there. 
This video really put into perspective how he really grew up poor. 
I’m remembering his stories about him running around barefoot, dealing with consistent power outages, and rats.

My Father loved Trujillo because he hates Haitian immigration. He also signed his mom a deed to a house to live in and raise her kids.
I’m sad to hear theres more Haitian immigrants there… 

Hearing them all speak in Spanish with a Dominican dialect, tone, and attitude takes me back to my Childhood. 
Thats all I heard all day growing up in a Dominican family.

textDisplay: Shout out from Canada. I've been to Puerta Plata 13 times now since I was young. textDisplay: Hi, I have found this video very interesting, actually first video which made me to write a comment on yt. I would like to share my experience from visiting Santo Domingo. Been in the US for work and travel, after some traveling I had some days before leaving to Europe, so I just bought the cheapest tickets and they were to the DR. Had some friends there I met in the US. Until I arrived, I did not really plan anything just booked some hotel in the Zona Colonial, my Spanish is poor so it was quite hard to comunicate. After checking into the hotel I went for a walk to explore the hotel. From the first look I saw that being caucasian really made a lot of people to look at me and even shout. I did not really like so much attention and I understood from that, that being white is considered being rich in DR. After some time a guy from Haiti came to me and wanted to be my guide, telling me it is a thing. We were comunicating in three languages french, spanish and english, we both knew a little bit of each at least, so we were talking about different things. After some time I did not feel comfortable anymore and he wanted money for the guiding and he invited me to his hair saloon, which I politely declined, gave him 50 pesos for the guide and went on my way. Back at the hotel I realised, that it was pretty dangerous and could have ended badly.  When I met my dominican friends, they said, that they are not getting around without a car and they said it was very dangerous for me. Tbh in some US cities I felt far more in danger. The rest of the stay was very pleasant, the people are very kind and I also like how people dance, especially girls :D I also love the style of the Zona Colonial. If you're going to go, its the best having a local friend with you or not be alone I suppose. Hope to come back soon! Love from Czech republic!

textDisplay:
The reason why the water in Rio Ozama is that color is due to the soil, not so much polution. The same is the case with Rio Haina.

That said, there is some polution but the water color is misleading.

The areas "Sabana Perdida", "Sabana Grande" and the other two or so used to be, like the name implies: Savanas but over time, people grabbed a piece of land and built their homes.

The dish you had is typically called: la bandera (the flag), it has our colors ... variety representing our culture or commonly found in every household.

While the area is of mostly lower income families, you will be surprised to find Doctors, Lawyers, Engineers, Athletes and all walks of life ...

As per your safety, 97% to 99% of Dominicans will jump in your defense ... thugs are not liked in the Island but they do exists ...

Oh, by the way, que lo que is very unique to DR and another greeting commonly used is "Dimelo Vacano!"

The Pineapple guy is Haitian, we can tell the moment they speak (specially if they have not grown up in DR) - Most of them are welcome, a very small number of them act up and are up to no good thus bringing bad rap to the Haitian community in DR. Overall, the two get alone pretty well.

textDisplay: During sometime I spent in the Dominican three years ago I did manage to go to the same areas as Kurt did in Santo Domingo.  It really was an eye opener let me say you have to be aware of your surroundings. It was blistering hot and humid, like in the 40's C  I travelled for three hours by a beat up old bus full of locals to get to Santo Dominican from the Vacation resort I was staying at. I was informed by staff at the resort that I would "end up dead" and was crazy to go there. I went.  For the best part the locals were very nice and enjoyed speaking with me but, it was a dangerous thing to do especially in some areas. Kurt has big Balls to be doing this alone but like me why travel if you really don't experience the true culture. Thanks Kurt it brought back many memories.

Yes xBUMSKIx I agree. Kurt eventually wins people over with his consistent outgoing-ness... I loved the friendship He struck up with the Swiss guy in Mexico. 👍🏼🤜🏼 But my hat also goes off to him, there's a healthy dose of good ol' South African no nonsense courage there and bold unfettered trust, which maybe is probably the reason no one has tried anything messed up yet. He seems to have a good radar going on, I think that is also very typical of Afrikaners, Blankes or Europeërs. Just down to Earth and strong forward like people. Still, I worry bro... I mean, I speak Spanish ... and I can feel on my skin some of the situations you go into. Much love, and let us know when you will close this chapter on these types of videos so we can all rest a little easier. lol ... I mean, there are people in some of those neighborhoods who prey precisely on people that venture out alone with courage like that, set up traps and stuff, but; I know you already know that. So stay vigilant my friend 💚
PS, we're all crossing our fingers that South Africa will end racism and unite as one people soon 🙏🏼
